  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally-obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex financial transactions. Key legal definitions typically include:\n\n1. Basic legal elements:\n- Concealing the source of illegally obtained funds\n- Transforming criminal proceeds into seemingly legitimate assets\n- Disguising the origin of money from criminal activities\n\n2. Common legal components:\n- Intentional financial transactions\n- Knowing the funds derive from criminal activity\n- Attempting to conceal or disguise the money's illegal source\n\n3. Typical stages of money laundering:\n- Placement (introducing illegal funds into financial system)\n- Layering (creating complex financial transactions)\n- Integration (making funds appear legitimate)\n\n4. Specific legal jurisdictions have variations, but generally criminalize:\n- Knowingly engaging in financial transactions with illegal proceeds\n- Attempting to conceal the nature of illegal funds\n- Conducting transactions designed to avoid reporting requirements\n\n5. Specific laws like the Bank Secrecy Act in the US provide detailed legal frameworks for defining and prosecuting money laundering.\n\nThese are general legal perspectives. Specific definitions can vary by jurisdiction and context.",
